{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17476447","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17476447"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:47:05+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:47:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13741"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13741","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13741"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.22,0.16,0.02,0.58]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6360"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"91196"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6360","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6360"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13741"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75021"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"93"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"1095"},{"type":"tags","id":"3549"},{"type":"tags","id":"3696"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"11812"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31208"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"91196","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/91196"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 14-year-old boy presents to the General Practice clinic with a six-month history of intermittent abdominal pain, diarrhoea and 4 kg weight loss. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. On examination, he appears thin but otherwise well with vital signs within normal limits. Abdominal examination reveals mild tenderness in the right lower quadrant. There is an erythematous, tender nodule on his right leg (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Irritable bowel syndrome","Coeliac disease","Ulcerative colitis","Infectious colitis","Crohn\u0027s disease"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most likely diagnosis in this patient is \u003Cstrong\u003ECrohn\u0027s disease\u003C/strong\u003E. Crohn\u0027s disease is a type of inflammatory bowel disease that can affect any part of the gastrointestinal tract from the mouth to the anus. It is characterised by transmural inflammation and skip lesions. Common presenting symptoms include abdominal pain, diarrhoea, and weight loss. Extraintestinal manifestations such as erythema nodosum (as seen in this patient) are also suggestive of Crohn\u0027s disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECommon extraintestinal manifestations of Crohn\u0027s disease include erythema nodosum, pyoderma gangrenosum, aphthous stomatitis, uveitis, episcleritis, peripheral arthritis, axial arthropathy, primary sclerosing cholangitis, and ankylosing spondylitis. These manifestations can occur in up to 40% of patients with Crohn\u0027s disease and may precede the onset of gastrointestinal symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn contrast, \u003Cstrong\u003Eulcerative colitis\u003C/strong\u003E is limited to the colon and is characterised by continuous inflammation involving the mucosa and submucosa. Patients with ulcerative colitis more commonly present with bloody diarrhoea. Extraintestinal manifestations are less common compared to Crohn\u0027s disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIrritable bowel syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E is a functional gastrointestinal disorder characterised by abdominal pain and altered bowel habits. However, it is not associated with weight loss or extraintestinal manifestations.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECoeliac disease\u003C/strong\u003E is an autoimmune disorder triggered by gluten ingestion. While it can cause abdominal pain and diarrhoea, it is not associated with erythema nodosum.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInfectious colitis\u003C/strong\u003E can cause acute diarrhoea but is usually self-limited and not associated with a chronic course or extraintestinal manifestations.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Crohn\u0027s disease can affect any part of the gastrointestinal tract and is characterised by skip lesions, while ulcerative colitis is limited to the colon with continuous inflammation.","Crohn\u0027s disease presents with abdominal pain, diarrhoea, and weight loss, while bloody diarrhoea is more characteristic of ulcerative colitis.","Extraintestinal manifestations such as arthritis, uveitis, and erythema nodosum are more common in Crohn\u0027s disease compared to ulcerative colitis."],"references":["Higuchi LM, Bousvaros A. Clinical presentation and diagnosis of inflammatory bowel disease in children. In: UpToDate [online]. 2024. Available at: https://www.uptodate.com/contents/clinical-presentation-and-diagnosis-of-inflammatory-bowel-disease-in-children","Veauthier B, Hornecker JR. Crohn\u0027s Disease: Diagnosis and Management. Am Fam Physician. 2018 Dec 1;98(11):661-669. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30485038/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75021"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13741"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21762"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21762","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21762"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/CbdgZ5oX4rhl8Pv852dmevMAK4oLym.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/CbdgZ5oX4rhl8P